Angular distributions were added for the (n,gamma) [MT=102], (n,p) 225 1451
[MT=103], and (n,d) [MT=104] reactions.  For the (n,gamma) reac-   225 1451
tion, we used the R-matrix calculation that gave the integrated    225 1451
cross section in the previous update (VII.1, below).  The same     225 1451
R-matrix calculation was used at low energies for the (n,p) and    225 1451
(n,d) reactions.  At higher energies we used the experimental      225 1451
data-based evaluation of Drosg and Otuka (M. Drosg and N.Otuka,    225 1451
Report INDC(AUS)-0019, January 2015). However, the results at      225 1451
lower energies were so close to the R-matrix results (this is      225 1451
noted in the report of Drosg and Otuka) that we ended up using     225 1451
their cross sections and Legendre coefficients over the whole      225 1451
range given for the (n,d) reaction, and used the R-matrix calcu-   225 1451
lation only to extend their results below 200 keV for the (n,p)    225 1451
reaction.  This extension preserves the values of the standard     225 1451
cross section below 50 keV.  Differences with the previous         225 1451
evaluation on the order of 10% occur in the (n,p) and (n,d) inte-  225 1451
grated  cross sections at energies above ~6-12 MeV due to the      225 1451
different experimental data Drosg and Otuka considered in their    225 1451
evaluation.                                                        225 1451
